info.remarks:
Circumstances
Found Sat. 19 Oct. 1991 by Mr. Lawley on the beach below Birling Gap. There had been a storm the previous day and the sea was now unusually low. He found the axe wedged between stones (not large boulders) at a point roughly 50 m west of the base of the steps, and 20-25 m from the then sea-line. A second object, seemingly of cast iron and 'knuckle duster' like was on the pebbles nearby.

Area find.

info.description: EL 146.9mm; EWe 37.7; Bst 31.7; Tbt 5.0; max T.sep. 1.7; Blp. 10.5[;]rounded stop crest - tendency to facetting - not regular; fairly crisp sep. angles; short upper blade sides emphasized by thin ribs, two sl. diverging short ribs between, mainly lost on rev face; marked constriction below stop, but only diffuse bevel on sides; thin stump of eq. fu. along much of sides, removed [...] from part of loop; moulding ripples inside on sep.; no def. info.description: Discovered by workmen digging a drainage inspection box immediately to the south of the front door of "Seaward", The Ridings, East Preston (TQ 068018). Found 18 inches deep in clay mould. Found July, 1954.[;]Late Bronze Age palstave with stop-ridge and loop. Two raised ribs below and almost at right angles to stop-ridge. Both flanges on one side damaged.
info.remarks: One of nine implements found at "Seaward" by workmen. This, and one small fragment of a palstave were brought to my notice at the Museum; extensive enquiries, however, failed to trace any others which were reputed to have been 'sold to a dealer for sixpence'; etc. The building firm concerned, also, was most un-cooperative. The workmen were questioned as to the appearance of the others and from their description it appears to have been a hoard of eight palstaves and one socketed axe.

info.description: Dimensions: L 164.3mm; We 38.2mm; Wbt 22.3mm; Bst. 37mm; Blp 9.3mm; T sep 16.6mm; Tbt 7.5mm[;]Typology: five short ribs on either face, outer ones slightly thinner - terminals emphasised by  forged bev.; angular blade edges; rounded st. and fg. crests - latter very narrow; slight bowing to butt faces[;]Manufacture: some fg. ends clipped by hammering; cg. fl. remains only on flange sides only - totally removed from butt and blade sides - some hammer marks here; part of cg. fl. quite sharp - untrimmed; small irregular bulbous mouldings on fg. and sl - defects; slight hammermark damage much of blade, with qt. distinct; edge bev. low down; cavities in one septum end - cg. flaws[;]Condition: butt top - broken surface - probably in manufacturing; edge basically in tact, blunted from patina flaking; crests on one face - corrosion chipped.[;]Attached Material: Chalky to fawn  matrix mainly in hollows

info.description: Dimensions: L 132.2mm; EWe 46.0mm; Wbt 24.5mm; Bst 34.0mm; Blp 8.6mm; T sep 15.2mm; Tbb 5.7 mm (approx)[;]Typology: five irregularly spaced ribs - 2 outer ones very thing - flatten at bases and merge out; angular square-ended septum; blade cast with a flare below decoration; rounded fg. crests - medium broad; inner edge of stop qt. angular bevelled underside; bev. on septum across fg. ends[;]Manufacture: blade faces cast or forged into 4 longitudinal facets - few individual hammer marks possibly discernible; broad stumps of cg. fl. - some practically or totally removed - hammer marks; hammer flattening of fg. ends; 2 valves of mould dislocated; loop asymmetric., septums different lengths;  asymmetric fg. section; small proj. on one side - cg. defect?; much of butt-end smoothed.[;]Condition: virtually all of edge lost - chipped to pale green and dark chocolate brown; fgs and sts mainly undamaged[;]Attached Material: light orangey-brown soil traces in many places

info.surface: Black to green-brown patina; localised patches of brighter green speckled texture surface; pocking and flaking, mainly close to blade edge, to light green dusty surface; chipping at edge also revealing dark brown smooth surface.
info.description: Dimensions: L 151.3mm; Wbl.e 35.6mm; Wbt 19.5mm; max B bt 5.5mm; T sep 14.5mm; B st. 31.7mm; Blp 10.2mm[;]Typology: crisp body angles to butt end, but each with facet, just below end; fg. crests mainly rounded to flat and undulating; underside of st. bevelled - reverse one more regular; constriction at top of blade not defined by neat side bevels; blade angles crisp; septum angles fairly crisp, corners little rounded, end little bowed; both septums offset to right at bottom[;]Manufacture: low fairly narrow stump of cg. fl. on loop - rounded with some battering; above loop and on central part of reverse side low broad flat-topped cg. fl with hammer marks, but no  sign lpg.; fully removed elsewhere on sides, where some suggestion of hammer marks, also on lower blade; very slight hollows immediately beneath stops on faces - probably cg. flaws; some irregularity on fg. insides - as cast[;]Condition: butt end a broken surface - untampered with; blade edge more or less intact, but not sharp, possibly due to det.; band of diagonal grmks. up on blade face - pres. modern but no diff. colour[;]Attached Material: butt soil traces, especially on butt end and under lp.

Humphreys, F.S.A. in the Transactions of the Birmingham Archaelogical Society for 1961-1962.

info.remarks: Found in 1934 in digging port hole in yard of a small holding known as "Mount Pleasant" c. 600 feet above sea level. "Mount Pleasant" is not named on 6"0-S. The impt. was found by D.G. Dicks, the owner of the building, at a depth of 3 ft.

info.description: Dimentions: L 154.4mm; We 59.3mm; Wst 32.3mm; Wbt 23.0mm; Bfg 26mm; Bst 27.5mm; Wt. 440.2 gms[;]Typology: fg. insides well sloped to rounded angles with slightly curved septum floor; end sub-rect.; shield rib begins at lower levels than fg./stop, and divided on either face by central rib; blade sec. near rect. - only slightly bowed faces; one sep rather longer than the other.[;]Manufacture: some dimpling undulations in patina extant - probably from moulding; cg. flash survives only as slight step, or differential surface condition; diffuse edge bevel probably originally sharp and quite steep[;]Condition: blade edge a little jagged - quite likely intact corrosion; fissures across base of 3 fgs just above stop - pres. dam.; butt close to orig. shape, but notch uncertain[;]Attached Material: chalky fawn soil deposit ingrained in patina in sep ends.

info.description: Dimensions: L 167 mm; We 75.8mm; W shoulder 27.5mm; Wbt 25.4mm; Bfg. 34.7mm; maxBst 30.5mm; maxTsep 8.5mm; Wt 545.4gms[;]Typology: shield depression on blade with no encircling rib; stop thick with round bevel - slightly dipped towards either flange; slight bar ridges on sides; cross-section - sep. floor curved, inside angles slightly rounded; fg. crests rounded; very diffuse bev. across fg. tops on butt[;]Manufacture: butt end broken surface from snapping off cg. jet; similar hole in one sep. end, one half partly filled with more vesicular metal; cg. flash well remoced for most part - evident as groove and/or ridge; neat high e. bev. plus two (or one on rev) close to edge; very slight blade tip hollows; dimpling on patina on sides and in septums - probably in the moulding; haammering of tops of two flanges has caused slight lipping on one side.[;]Condition: some minor denting of edge, stretches fairly sharp; tips both a little blunted - one retains patina, the other + all of reverse blade face polished to bright gold colour by finder; crack across the base of one fg - damage? - another surface fissure across one corner of blade

info.remarks: One of nine implements found at "Seaward" by workmen. This, and one small fragment of a palstave were brought to my notice at the Museum: extensive enquiries, however, failed to trace any others which were reputed to have been 'sold to a dealer for sixpence';'given to my child for his school museum'; etc. The building firm concerned, also, was most unco- operative. The workmen were questioned as to the appearance of the others and from their description it appears to have been a hoard of eight palstaves and one socketed axe.

rounded corners to septum, and marked constriction just below stop - but not distinct bevels ; crinonline flange profiles ; v. square blade angles in section ; slight longitudinal drepression in centre of septums ; almost vert.underside to stop ; bl. faces v. sl. dished ; pore hokles at end of one sep and in butt end ; sl. ridge remains of cg. fl. ; marked hammering of bl. e. forming diffuse e. bev. and deep bl. tip hollows; hammering of flange ends causing dishing of upper flange sides.

"mount pleasant" is not named on 6" o.s. lxxx s.w., but it is the building 530 yds sse of curland church, &, as the crow flies, only 680 yds nne of the "beacon" od castle neroche (see proc: som: arch: soc: xlix. ii 23-53). the impt. was found by dg. dicks, the owner of the building, at a depth of 3 ft.
info.description: The flanges taper from the prominent stop ridge towards the butt: on both faces of the palstave is a well defined tongue shaped ridge which protrudes from the stop ridge towards the cutting edge. The fin down the middle of both sides (casting mark) has not been entirely removed. Both the cutting edge & the butt have been considerably hammered. In places the bright surface of the bronze indicates "polishing up" by the finder.

info.description: Typology: sl. irreg. bev. across fg. tops on sep. ; one sep. little wider than other - both curved bottoms in cross-sec. with rounded angles ; fg. and stop crests neat rounded - no distict bevels ; stops little depress in centre ; short fg. extensions onto bd. with flattened crests tending to splay at bases; midrib low rounded [...] [?bumps] without crisp bevels - one extends virt. to e. bev, other higher, but as short as fg. extensions ; sides sl. bowed in cross-sec. ; e.g. fl. remains as v. broad low rounded bump - less pronounced on either side, virt. all trace removed on bl. sides, with some hammer rippling; dimples generally even sur. - hmks or moulding?  Swallow hole in end of one sep.,depression in other; e. bevs. little diffuse - assoc. hmks most of bl. e. irreg. - prob. from chipping of p., but one large chip def. anc. with p. intact; p. frag. also in one butt depression - irreg. line prob. orig. ; 2 or 3 small gougings of p., prob. recent, including one blade angle forming facet ; short intact stretches of bl. e. suggest one fairly sharp

info.description:
L 154.4mm; We 59.3; Wst 32.3; Wbb 23.0; Bfg 26.0; Bst. 27.5; Wt 440.2 
Typology: Fg insides well sloped to rounded angles with sl. curved sep. floor; sep end sub rect; shield rib begins at lower level than fg/stop, and divided on either face by central rib; bl sec near rect - only sl. bowed faces; one sep rather longer than the other. 
Manufacture: some dimpling/undulations in p. extant prob from moulding; cg flash survives only as sl. step, or differential sur. condition; diffuse e.ber prob. originally sharp and quite steep;
Condition: bl. e. a little jagged - quite likely intact before corrosion; fissures across based of 3 fgs. just above stop- poss dam.; butt close to orig shape, but notch uncertain.
Surface: olive green p. preserved in small patches on sides and blade, and over most of the septums; mainly flaked to fir green dry sur. with lighter green pockings; small areas on bl. stripped down to gold metal. 
Conserved at London Institute of Archaeology lab - lab no 3889.
Chalky fawn soil desposit engrained in p. in sep ends. 
Context single find

info.description: Typology: shield depression on blade with no encircling rib; stop thick with round bevel - slightly dipped towards either flange; sl. bar ridges on sides; cross-section - sep. floor curved, inside angles sl. rounded, fg crests rounded; v. diffuse bev. across fg. tops on butt;[;]Manufacture: butt end a broken sur. from snapping off cg.jet; shallow hole in one sep. end, one half partly filled with more vesicular metal; cg. flash well removed for most part - evident as groove and or ridge; neat high e. bev. plus two (or one on sev.) close to edge; v. sl. blade tip hollows; dimpling in p. on sides and in septums - prob. in the moulding; hammering of tops of two flanges has caused sl. lipping on one side.[;]Condition: some minor denting of edge, stretches fairly sharp; tips both a little blunted - one retains patina, the other & all of rev. bl. face polished to bright gold colour by finder;  crack across the base of one fg. - dam? - another sur. fissure across one corner of blade;
